\subsubsection*{Exercise: Filtering based on variance}
In this exercise we filter the expression data based on the row--mad (mean
absolute deviation) instead of the row median. This
can be conveniently done using the function
\Rfunction{rowMads}.

\begin{enumerate}[label=(\emph{\alph*})]
\item A histogram of the square root of the mads will be
roughly symmetric. Fit a null model via visual inspection.
\item Use the 5\% quantile of this model as a threshold. Compare
the thresholded genes to the intensity based approach. Is the overlap
very large? (HINT use the function \Rfunction{table} to check this)
\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection*{Solution: Filtering based on variance}

<<variance based filtering, results='hide', eval = FALSE>>=
# a
#######################################################
load(file.path("dataMAWorkflow", "TinaEXP.RData"))
TinaSqrtMads = sqrt(rowMads(exprs(TinaEset)))
tmp <- hist(TinaSqrtMads, 100, col="lavender", freq = FALSE)

emp.mu <- tmp$breaks[which.max(tmp$density)] + 0.005
emp.sd <- mad(TinaSqrtMads)/4
eta0 <- 0.40
lines(sort(TinaSqrtMads), eta0*dnorm(sort(TinaSqrtMads),
      	mean = emp.mu , sd = emp.sd ),
				col = "coral3", lwd =4)
# b
#######################################################

### find 5% quantile of fitted null model
thresh.mad <- qnorm(0.05 / eta0, emp.mu, emp.sd)
idx.thresh.mad <- TinaSqrtMads > thresh.mad
table( idx.thresh.mad )

## overlap
prop.table(table(idx.thresh.mad , idx.thresh.median ))
@

